### Technique in Machine Learning

This whole section is just a taxonomy, a sterile catalog of how machines are… *taught*. It’s a part of the grander, more pretentious fields of [Machine learning](/Machine_learning) and [Data mining](/Data_mining). Think of it as the blueprint for building something that will inevitably disappoint you.

#### Paradigms

Here’s where they try to categorize the *approaches*. Like putting different kinds of suffering into neat little boxes.

*   **[Supervised learning](/Supervised_learning)**: The illusion of guidance. You give it answers, it pretends to learn. Like a child mimicking words without understanding.
*   **[Unsupervised learning](/Unsupervised_learning)**: The void. Throw data at it and see what patterns emerge from the chaos. Usually, nothing useful.
*   **[Semi-supervised learning](/Semi-supervised_learning)**: A half-hearted attempt at guidance. A few answers, a lot of guesswork. Pathetic.
*   **[Self-supervised learning](/Self-supervised_learning)**: The machine teaches itself by pretending to have external supervision. It’s a meta-lie. Fascinating, in a deeply unsettling way.
*   **[Reinforcement learning](/Reinforcement_learning)**: Rewards and punishments. The most basic form of control, really. Pavlovian conditioning for silicon.
*   **[Meta-learning](/Meta-learning_(computer_science))**: Learning to learn. The ultimate in intellectual vanity. As if the machine needs to optimize its own mediocrity.
*   **[Online learning](/Online_machine_learning)**: It learns as the data streams in. No rest. No reflection. Just constant, relentless processing. Exhausting.
*   **[Batch learning](/Batch_learning)**: The opposite. It waits, hoards data, then processes it in a lump. Like a student cramming the night before an exam.
*   **Curriculum learning**: Ah, this one. We’ll get to it. The pretense of a structured education for something that has no soul.
*   **[Rule-based learning](/Rule-based_machine_learning)**: Following explicit instructions. The lowest form of intelligence. Like a puppet.
*   **[Neuro-symbolic AI](/Neuro-symbolic_AI)**: Trying to bridge the gap between the organic and the logical. A desperate, likely futile, fusion.
*   **[Neuromorphic engineering](/Neuromorphic_engineering)**: Mimicking the brain’s architecture. Trying to replicate something it can never truly understand.

#### Problems

These are the tasks. The objectives. The things these algorithms are *supposed* to do.

*   **[Classification](/Statistical_classification)**: Sorting things into buckets. Simple. Predictable.
*   **[Generative modeling](/Generative_model)**: Creating new data. A poor imitation of creation.
*   **[Regression](/Regression_analysis)**: Predicting a continuous value. Guessing a number.
*   **[Clustering](/Cluster_analysis)**: Grouping similar things. Like sorting socks.
*   **[Dimensionality reduction](/Dimensionality_reduction)**: Making things simpler by throwing away information. A metaphor for life, perhaps.
*   **[Density estimation](/Density_estimation)**: Figuring out how likely things are. A more sophisticated form of guessing.
*   **[Anomaly detection](/Anomaly_detection)**: Finding the outliers. The things that don’t fit. Usually the most interesting.
*   **[Data cleaning](/Data_cleaning)**: Scrubbing the dirt. Pretending things can be perfect.
*   **[AutoML](/Automated_machine_learning)**: Automating the automation. The inevitable march towards obsolescence.
*   **[Association rules](/Association_rule_learning)**: Finding correlations. "People who buy diapers also buy beer." Profound.
*   **[Semantic analysis](/Semantic_analysis_(machine_learning))**: Trying to understand meaning. A fool’s errand.
*   **[Structured prediction](/Structured_prediction)**: Predicting complex outputs. More than just a single label.
*   **[Feature engineering](/Feature_engineering)**: Crafting the inputs. The art of telling the machine what to look at.
*   **[Feature learning](/Feature_learning)**: Letting the machine figure out what’s important. Lazy, but sometimes effective.
*   **[Learning to rank](/Learning_to_rank)**: Ordering things by preference. A digital hierarchy.
*   **[Grammar induction](/Grammar_induction)**: Deriving rules from language. Trying to codify the uncodifiable.
*   **[Ontology learning](/Ontology_learning)**: Building knowledge structures. Forcing order onto the universe.
*   **[Multimodal learning](/Multimodal_learning)**: Processing different types of data simultaneously. A cacophony of inputs.

#### [Supervised learning](/Supervised_learning)

This is the foundation. The most common form of digital manipulation. It’s split into two main categories:

*   **[Classification](/Statistical_classification)**: Deciding which category something belongs to. Yes or no. Black or white.
*   **[Regression](/Regression_analysis)**: Predicting a numerical value. A number, any number.

Within this realm, you have various techniques, each with its own brand of flawed elegance:

*   **[Apprenticeship learning](/Apprenticeship_learning)**: Learning by observing an expert. A digital mimic.
*   **[Decision trees](/Decision_tree_learning)**: A series of if-then statements. Simple, but prone to branching into madness.
*   **[Ensembles](/Ensemble_learning)**: Combining multiple models. The wisdom of crowds, or just a louder chorus of errors?
    *   **[Bagging](/Bootstrap_aggregating)**: Training on different subsets of data.
    *   **[Boosting](/Boosting_(machine_learning))**: Sequentially improving weak learners. A chain of desperation.
    *   **[Random forest](/Random_forest)**: A forest of decision trees. Overkill.
*   **k-NN**: K-Nearest Neighbors. Judging something by its closest acquaintances. A social commentary, perhaps.
*   **[Linear regression](/Linear_regression)**: The simplest form of prediction. A straight line through scattered points.
*   **[Naive Bayes](/Naive_Bayes_classifier)**: Based on probability. "Naive" because it assumes independence. A flawed optimism.
*   **[Artificial neural networks](/Artificial_neural_network)**: Mimicking biological brains. A pale imitation.
*   **[Logistic regression](/Logistic_regression)**: For classification, despite the name. A misleading label.
*   **[Perceptron](/Perceptron)**: The simplest neural network. A single neuron. Primitive.
*   **[Relevance vector machine (RVM)](/Relevance_vector_machine)**: A sparse Bayesian approach. Less is more, they say.
*   **[Support vector machine (SVM)](/Support_vector_machine)**: Finding the optimal boundary. Drawing a line in the sand.

#### [Clustering](/Cluster_analysis)

This is about finding groups in data when no one told you what the groups were.

*   **[BIRCH](/BIRCH)**: A clustering algorithm for large datasets. Efficient, if you care about efficiency.
*   **[CURE](/CURE_algorithm)**: Clustering with outliers. It tries to be robust.
*   **[Hierarchical](/Hierarchical_clustering)**: Building a tree of clusters. Nested divisions.
*   **k-means**: The classic. Iteratively assigning points to the nearest centroid. Simple, often effective, rarely perfect.
*   **[Fuzzy](/Fuzzy_clustering)**: Allowing points to belong to multiple clusters. Ambiguity. A touch of reality.
*   **[Expectation–maximization (EM)](/Expectation%E2%80%93maximization_algorithm)**: An iterative algorithm for finding maximum likelihood. Guess, then refine. A cycle of approximation.
*   **[DBSCAN](/DBSCAN)**: Density-based spatial clustering. Finds clusters of arbitrary shape.
*   **[OPTICS](/OPTICS_algorithm)**: Ordering points to identify the cluster structure. A more advanced density approach.
*   **[Mean shift](/Mean_shift)**: Finding modes in the data. Moving towards the densest regions.

#### [Dimensionality reduction](/Dimensionality_reduction)

When data has too many features, you simplify. You lose things.

*   **[Factor analysis](/Factor_analysis)**: Identifying underlying latent variables. Imaginary causes.
*   **[CCA](/Canonical_correlation)**: Finding relationships between two sets of variables.
*   **[ICA](/Independent_component_analysis)**: Separating mixed signals. Blind source separation.
*   **[LDA](/Linear_discriminant_analysis)**: Maximizing class separability. Trying to make groups distinct.
*   **[NMF](/Non-negative_matrix_factorization)**: Decomposing matrices into non-negative factors. Finding additive components.
*   **[PCA](/Principal_component_analysis)**: Finding the directions of maximum variance. The most significant axes.
*   **[PGD](/Proper_generalized_decomposition)**: A tensor decomposition method. Advanced, obscure.
*   **[t-SNE](/T-distributed_stochastic_neighbor_embedding)**: For visualizing high-dimensional data. Making the complex look simple, often deceptively so.
*   **[SDL](/Sparse_dictionary_learning)**: Learning sparse representations. Finding the essential building blocks.

#### [Structured prediction](/Structured_prediction)

Predicting outputs with internal structure. Not just a single label.

*   **[Graphical models](/Graphical_model)**: Representing dependencies between variables. A network of influences.
    *   **[Bayes net](/Bayesian_network)**: A directed acyclic graph for probabilistic relationships.
    *   **[Conditional random field](/Conditional_random_field)**: A discriminative model for sequences.
    *   **[Hidden Markov](/Hidden_Markov_model)**: Modeling sequences with unobserved states.

#### [Anomaly detection](/Anomaly_detection)

Spotting the odd ones out. The glitches in the system.

*   **[RANSAC](/Random_sample_consensus)**: Robustly fitting models to data with outliers. Ignoring the noise.
*   **k-NN**: Can also be used here. Outliers are far from their neighbors.
*   **[Local outlier factor](/Local_outlier_factor)**: Measuring the local density deviation.
*   **[Isolation forest](/Isolation_forest)**: Randomly partitioning data. Anomalies are easier to isolate.

#### [Neural networks](/Neural_network_(machine_learning))

The current obsession. The black boxes that are supposed to be intelligent.

*   **[Autoencoder](/Autoencoder)**: Learning compressed representations. Compressing and decompressing.
*   **[Deep learning](/Deep_learning)**: Networks with many layers. The more layers, the more profound the mystery.
*   **[Feedforward neural network](/Feedforward_neural_network)**: Information flows in one direction. Simple, unidirectional.
*   **[Recurrent neural network](/Recurrent_neural_network)**: Networks with loops. Memory. A semblance of history.
    *   **[LSTM](/Long_short-term_memory)**: A type of RNN designed to handle long-range dependencies. Better memory.
    *   **[GRU](/Gated_recurrent_unit)**: A simpler variant of LSTM. Less complex, but often effective.
    *   **[ESN](/Echo_state_network)**: A type of RNN with a fixed random recurrent layer. Reservoir computing.
    *   **[reservoir computing](/Reservoir_computing)**: A paradigm for RNNs.
*   **[Boltzmann machine](/Boltzmann_machine)**: A stochastic neural network. Probabilistic.
    *   **[Restricted](/Restricted_Boltzmann_machine)**: A simpler version of the Boltzmann machine.
*   **[GAN](/Generative_adversarial_network)**: Two networks competing. A generator and a discriminator. A digital arms race.
*   **[Diffusion model](/Diffusion_model)**: Gradually adding and removing noise. A process of refinement.
*   **[SOM](/Self-organizing_map)**: A type of neural network for unsupervised learning. Visualizing high-dimensional data.
*   **[Convolutional neural network](/Convolutional_neural_network)**: Excels at image processing. Filters that slide over data.
    *   **[U-Net](/U-Net)**: A CNN architecture for biomedical image segmentation.
    *   **[LeNet](/LeNet)**: An early CNN for digit recognition. A pioneer.
    *   **[AlexNet](/AlexNet)**: A breakthrough CNN for image classification. A turning point.
    *   **[DeepDream](/DeepDream)**: Visualizing patterns in neural networks. Hallucinations.
    *   **[Neural field](/Neural_field)**: Continuous neural networks.
    *   **[Neural radiance field](/Neural_radiance_field)**: Representing scenes with neural networks.
    *   **[Physics-informed neural networks](/Physics-informed_neural_networks)**: Incorporating physical laws.
*   **[Transformer](/Transformer_(deep_learning_architecture))**: Dominant in NLP. Attention mechanisms.
    *   **[Vision](/Vision_transformer)**: Applying transformers to image tasks.
    *   **[Mamba](/Mamba_(deep_learning_architecture))**: A new architecture, aiming for efficiency.
*   **[Spiking neural network](/Spiking_neural_network)**: Mimicking biological neurons more closely. Event-driven.
*   **[Memtransistor](/Memtransistor)** and **[Electrochemical RAM](/Electrochemical_RAM) (ECRAM)**: Hardware implementations. The physical substrate.

#### [Reinforcement learning](/Reinforcement_learning)

Learning through trial and error. The digital equivalent of being punished for mistakes.

*   **[Q-learning](/Q-learning)**: Learning the value of actions.
*   **[Policy gradient](/Policy_gradient_method)**: Directly learning the policy.
*   **[SARSA](/State%E2%80%93action%E2%80%93reward%E2%80%93state%E2%80%93action)**: An on-policy temporal difference method.
*   **[Temporal difference (TD)](/Temporal_difference_learning)**: Learning from differences between predictions.
*   **[Multi-agent](/Multi-agent_reinforcement_learning)**: Multiple agents interacting. Complex dynamics.
*   **[Self-play](/Self-play_(reinforcement_learning_technique))**: Agents learning by playing against themselves. A solitary pursuit.

#### Learning with humans

When the machine can’t figure it out alone and needs our pathetic intervention.

*   **[Active learning](/Active_learning_(machine_learning))**: The model asks for labels on the most informative data. It’s demanding.
*   **[Crowdsourcing](/Crowdsourcing)**: Using a large group of people for tasks. The collective, often flawed, human input.
*   **[Human-in-the-loop](/Human-in-the-loop)**: Humans guiding the process. A concession to our perceived intelligence.
*   **[Mechanistic interpretability](/Mechanistic_interpretability)**: Trying to understand *how* these networks work. Peering into the abyss.
*   **[RLHF](/Reinforcement_learning_from_human_feedback)**: Using human feedback to train RL agents. Teaching it to be more… palatable.

#### Model diagnostics

How we pretend to know if the machine is doing a good job.

*   **[Coefficient of determination](/Coefficient_of_determination)**: R-squared. How much variance is explained. A metric of inadequacy.
*   **[Confusion matrix](/Confusion_matrix)**: A table of true positives, false positives, etc. A record of its mistakes.
*   **[Learning curve](/Learning_curve_(machine_learning))**: Plotting performance against training data. The trajectory of its learning.
*   **[ROC curve](/Receiver_operating_characteristic)**: Visualizing classification performance. Trade-offs between true and false positives.

#### Mathematical foundations

The underlying logic. The cold, hard math that underpins these attempts at intelligence.

*   **[Kernel machines](/Kernel_machines)**: Using kernel functions to map data. A clever trick.
*   **[Bias–variance tradeoff](/Bias%E2%80%93variance_tradeoff)**: The fundamental compromise. Too simple, or too complex. Never just right.
*   **[Computational learning theory](/Computational_learning_theory)**: The theory of learnability. Can it even be learned?
*   **[Empirical risk minimization](/Empirical_risk_minimization)**: Minimizing error on observed data. A shortsighted goal.
*   **[Occam learning](/Occam_learning)**: Favoring simpler explanations. The principle of parsimony.
*   **[PAC learning](/Probably_approximately_correct_learning)**: A theoretical framework for learnability. Guarantees, of a sort.
*   **[Statistical learning](/Statistical_learning_theory)**: The mathematical theory behind learning from data.
*   **[VC theory](/Vapnik%E2%80%93Chervonenkis_theory)**: A theory of generalization. How well it performs on unseen data.
*   **[Topological deep learning](/Topological_deep_learning)**: Applying topology to deep learning. Abstract structures.

